        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} reports several years of intermittent knee discomfort that has become more persistent over the last year, with no single major traumatic event recalled. He has no history suggesting an acute infectious process, urinary-source bacteremia, or unusual systemic complication; this negative framing is intentional because the provided evidence on osteomyelitis and urinary infections concerns rare scenarios not applicable here and should not be extrapolated into this patient without support [PMID:32913861, PMID:38148952].\n\nHe is overweight, has a mostly physically demanding work history, and has become less active as knee pain has worsened. He uses occasional over-the-counter pain medicine with partial relief. There is no known inflammatory arthritis diagnosis, and no prior knee surgery. He has not been hospitalized recently.\n\nSocially, {patientName} drinks alcohol socially on weekends and does not use illicit drugs. He is a former smoker who quit years ago. He wants to stay active enough to keep working and continue family outings. He has not previously had specialist orthopedic assessment for this problem."
          }
        ]
      }
